{
  "response_text": "The count of E-RO households exhibits high variability across simulation runs, diverging rapidly from the initial value of 20 households at time step 0. Within the first 10-20 time steps, the population spreads across the full range from near-zero to 40-42 households.\n\nSeveral runs show transient peaks of 35-42 E-RO households occurring between time steps 15 and 40, followed by declines to stabilization levels of 23-28 households by time step 50. These populations persist through time step 100 with minor fluctuations between 22 and 27 households.\n\nOther runs stabilize at intermediate levels, maintaining populations of 15-25 households from approximately time step 40 onward, with continued variability ranging between 15 and 30 households.\n\nA third group experiences sustained declines to low population levels. By time step 30, these runs reach counts of 0-10 households. Several achieve complete extinction (0 households) by time steps 60-65, maintaining zero levels through the remainder of the simulation. Others stabilize at low non-zero levels of approximately 5-10 households from time step 60 to 100.\n\nBy time step 100, the E-RO population is distributed across three main clusters: a high cluster at 23-26 households, a middle cluster at 15-18 households, and a low cluster at 0-8 households.\n\nThe dynamics suggest that under stochastic rainfall conditions (mean 200, standard deviation 100) and competition with learning-capable strategies (E-LBD and E-RO-SL1), the non-learning E-RO strategy experiences path-dependent outcomes. The strategy can achieve temporary dominance with counts exceeding 35-40 households, can stabilize at levels comparable to or exceeding the initial population, or can be displaced to extinction. The decline from transient peaks of 40+ to stable levels of 25-27 in high-performing runs indicates competitive pressure from adaptive strategies or differential household mortality favoring non-E-RO types over the medium term."
}

